{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489838"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:32:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:32:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"756"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/756"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.09,0.04,0.4,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108936"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/756"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91305"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4228"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33488"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42140"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108936"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 89-year-old man attends the clinic for advice about a lesion on his face (Image). This has been present for about eight years, has not shown any obvious change and it does not bother him - but the patient\u0027s son said he should get it seen to. The patient had a small myocardial infarct two months ago and is currently on dual anti-platelet therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Review in six months","Imiquimod topic cream","Topical liquid nitrogen","Excisional biopsy with a 2 mm margin","Excise with a 5-10 mm margin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of lentigo maligna - or Hutchinson\u0027s melanotic freckle. It is characteristically found on the faces of elderly patients who have had excessive sun exposure and will have been present for many years. It is a subtype of melanoma-in-situ. Unlike other subtypes of melanoma, it can remain indolent for several years before progressing into an invasive melanoma. The risk of invasive transformation is reported to range 2-5%. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHence, in younger patients or in elderly patients who are otherwise fit and healthy, the current recommendation is to have the lesion \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgically biopsied with a 2mm margin\u003C/strong\u003E. Depending on results this may then be followed by \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete wide excision with 5-10mm margins.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever in this case as this lesion has remained unchanged for many years and the patient is elderly, it would be quite reasonable to \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeep it under close review\u003C/strong\u003E - particularly as the patient does not appear to be bothered about it. In addition, the patient is currently on dual anti-platelet therapy and any decision on surgical excision should be deferred until a few more months have elapsed. A careful discussion has to be done with the patient and his family and carefully documented.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther options of treatment include the use of \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical imiquimod\u003C/strong\u003E, but this agent can be associated with an intense local inflammatory reaction and is currently 2nd line agent in patients where surgical resection is not feasible. \u003Cstrong\u003ETopical liquid nitrogen\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate for lentigo maligna as it does not adequately treat the deeper components of the lesion and could mask signs of progression to invasive melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The possibility of progression to melanoma should be considered in all cases of lentigo maligna.","Management decisions of suspicious facial lesions should balance risk of progression with patient factors including age and anticoagulation status.","Surgical excision remains first-line treatment for lentigo maligna when feasible."],"references":["Robinson M, Primiero C, Guitera P, et al. Evidence-Based Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Patients with Lentigo Maligna. Dermatology 2020; 236:111-16. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31639788/","Ungureanu L, Vasilovici AF, Trufin II, et al. Lentigo Maligna Treatment\u2014An Update. J Clin Med. 2024;13:2527. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38731056/","Adybeik D, Ciranni D, Alaei L. Punch biopsy is best avoided for clinically suspicious pigmented lesions. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2019;48:354-6. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/june/punch-biopsy-is-best-avoided-for-clinically-suspic"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91305"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"756"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19668"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19668"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4556d2cc-6018-4294-99e4-2c283b5359ef.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4556d2cc-6018-4294-99e4-2c283b5359ef.jpg","isPr